The cleaning agents in Windex are two alcohols and ammonium hydroxide.
Alcohols typically have a very low vaporization temperature (they're volatile) and will be evaporated along with the water.
Ammonium hydroxide (NH4OH) will come to equilibrium with ammonia (NH3) in water; ammonia is volatile as well and will be extracted with the water. The pH of the solution is a big factor in the stressing the reaction toward ammonia (particularly, basic conditions stress the reaction more toward ammonia). Therefore, the higher the pH, the more ammonia we can expect to lose.
With less ammonia (a weak base) remaining in the freeze dry tray, the pH can be expected to be lower in the reconsituted cleaner. Check the pH before dehydration and after re-hydration and I imagine they'll be pretty different.
